TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effect of School Choice on Participants: Evidence from Randomized Lotteries
AU  - Cullen, Julie Berry
AU  - Jacob, Brian A
AU  - Levitt, Steven
Y1  - 2006/09/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2006.00702.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1191
EP  - 1230
VL  - 74
IS  - 5
KW  - School choice
KW  - randomized lottery
KW  - student outcomes
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2006.00702.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - School choice has become an increasingly prominent strategy for enhancing academic achievement. To evaluate the impact on participants, we exploit randomized lotteries that determine high school admission in the Chicago Public Schools. Compared to those students who lose lotteries, students who win attend high schools that are better in a number of dimensions, including peer achievement and attainment levels. Nonetheless, we find little evidence that winning a lottery provides any systematic benefit across a wide variety of traditional academic measures. Lottery winners do, however, experience improvements on a subset of nontraditional outcome measures, such as self-reported disciplinary incidents and arrest rates.
ER  - 

